article.description: The Connecticut Sun moved a game closer to securing homecourt advantage throughout the playoffs with an 84-70 win over the Charlotte Sting on Thursday.
article.headline: Sun near homecourt advantage with win
article.linkText: Whalen's career-high 28 paces Sun past Sting
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Lindsay Whalen got the Connecticut Sun
off to a fast start, and the Charlotte Sting spent the rest of the
game in pursuit.

Whalen scored a career-high 28 points and the Sun moved a game
closer to securing homecourt advantage throughout the playoffs with
an 84-70 win over the Sting on Thursday night.

"We just stepped back and let her go," teammate Nykesha Sales
said. "You've got to be athletic to keep up with her."

The Sun (24-6) began the day with a two-game edge over Western
Conference-leading Sacramento, which played San Antonio later
Thursday. The Sun need two more wins, a combination of a win and a
Sacramento loss, or two Monarchs losses to clinch homecourt
advantage.

Taj McWilliams-Franklin finished with 24 points and 11 rebounds
for the Sun, who have already wrapped up their second-straight
Eastern Conference title.

Whalen also had a team-high six assists and was 10-of-13 from
the free throw line. Sales finished with 14 points and had the only
3-pointer of the game.

Tangela Smith led last-place Charlotte (4-26) with 15 points.
Sheri Sam and Adrienne Goodson added 10 apiece.

Connecticut, leading 35-33 at the break, pushed the tempo to
start the second half and extended its lead to as many as 18
points.

"It felt like a track meet," Whalen said. "I was getting a
little winded out there. I just wanted to stay aggressive, stay in
the middle and create things that way."

The Sun came out with a quick tempo to start the game, with
Whalen leading the way. She hit three straight buckets, two of them
on the fastbreak, and Connecticut breezed to a 14-6 lead in the
first four minutes.

"I got a few layups and my teammates were giving me great
passes," she said. "At that point I started to feel good and felt
my energy was up."

Charlotte quickly got back into it, crashing the boards to
kick-start their transition game. Smith accounted for all the
scoring an 8-0 run. Her driving layup with 12:18 left pulled the
Sting even at 16-all.

A pair of free throws by Caity Matter on the Sting's next
possession gave Charlotte its first lead with 11:13 left.

The tempo on both sides began to slow down as the teams totaled
22 fouls in the opening period. Whalen and Sales each had three
fouls in the first half.

"The second half we didn't come back with the same intensity,"
Charlotte coach Muggsy Bogues said. "When you turn the ball over,
especially against a team like that, it is going to be very
difficult to get back in the ball game."

The Sting have lost five of six since Bogues replaced general
manager Trudi Lacey as coach on Aug. 3.

"They're playing that role of the spoiler," Whalen said.
"They want to get in there and knock people off. From the start
tonight we knew it was going to be a tough game. In the first half,
they made it really tough."
